  'caf86a67-120e-4a67-80bb-690cf130a765',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Bun's bun.lock — Lockfile Format, Integrity, and Dependency Auditing$escape$,
  $escape$Bun uses a binary lockfile (`bun.lock`) by default, which is faster to parse than JSON-based alternatives. Run `bun install --save-text-lockfile` to generate a human-readable `bun.lockb`-equivalent in text format for easier diffs in PRs. The lockfile pins exact resolved versions and integrity hashes for every package in the dependency tree — including transitive ones.

To audit dependencies for known vulnerabilities, Bun integrates with the npm advisory database via `bun audit`. It outputs severity levels (critical, high, moderate, low) and affected package paths. For CI pipelines, `bun audit --level high` exits non-zero only on high/critical findings.

Version ranges in `package.json` follow semver as expected. Use `bun update <pkg>` to bump a specific package within its declared range, or `bun update` to update all. To lock a package to an exact version without the `^` prefix, pass `--exact` during install: `bun add --exact react`. Always commit `bun.lock` — it ensures reproducible installs across machines and CI runners.$escape$,
  $escape$# Install deps and generate text lockfile for readable diffs
bun install --save-text-lockfile

# Audit for vulnerabilities; fail CI on high/critical only
bun audit --level high

# Add a package pinned to exact version (no ^ range)
bun add --exact zod

# Update a single package within its semver range
bun update hono

# Verify lockfile integrity without installing
bun install --frozen-lockfile$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
