INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '99b7707e-d78b-4130-8215-2684ad89263f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Bun's Standard Library — What's Built In vs What You Still Need npm For$escape$,
  $escape$Bun ships with a surprisingly complete standard library that eliminates many common npm dependencies. Built-in: `Bun.file()` for fast file I/O, `Bun.serve()` for HTTP servers, `Bun.hash()` (Wyhash/xxHash/CRC32), `Bun.password.hash()` and `Bun.password.verify()` for bcrypt/argon2, `Bun.TOML.parse()`, `Bun.Glob` for pattern matching, `Bun.sleep()`, `Bun.which()`, and a native `WebSocket` server baked into `Bun.serve()`. The `node:crypto`, `node:fs`, `node:path`, and `node:zlib` Node.js compatibility modules are also fully implemented.

What you still need third-party packages for: complex JWT handling (jose, jsonwebtoken), ORMs (Drizzle, Prisma), schema validation (Zod), date manipulation (date-fns), and any framework-level routing beyond `Bun.serve()`'s basic `fetch` handler. Notably, `Bun.serve()` has no built-in middleware pipeline — reach for Hono or Elysia if you need composable middleware. Email sending, PDF generation, and queue clients also remain ecosystem territory.$escape$,
  $escape$// All of this runs with zero npm installs
const file = Bun.file("./data.json");
const json = await file.json();

const hashed = await Bun.password.hash("hunter2", { algorithm: "argon2id" });
const valid = await Bun.password.verify("hunter2", hashed);

const glob = new Bun.Glob("src/**/*.ts");
for await (const path of glob.scan(".")) {
  console.log(path);
}

// Still needs: npm install zod
import { z } from "zod";
const schema = z.object({ name: z.string() });$escape$,
