INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e17580b3-2bb1-4965-8bc0-6c55b14456c3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Bun's Built-in REPL and Debugger — Zero-Config Dev Tooling$escape$,
  $escape$Bun ships a TypeScript-aware REPL out of the box — run `bun repl` and you get top-level `await`, full ESM imports, and live access to Bun APIs without any setup. Import a local module mid-session with `await import('./utils')` and start poking at it instantly.

For debugging, Bun implements the WebKit Inspector Protocol. Pass `--inspect` to start a WebSocket debug server on `ws://127.0.0.1:6499` by default. Open `chrome://inspect` or use VS Code's "Attach" launch config to connect. Use `--inspect-brk` to pause on the first line and wait for a client — essential for debugging startup logic.

Bun's VS Code extension hooks into this natively: add a launch config with `"runtime": "bun"` and `"request": "launch"` and F5 just works, with breakpoints, watch expressions, and call stacks. No `ts-node`, no `tsx`, no separate compile step. The extension also wraps `bun-types` to wire up accurate autocomplete for `Bun.serve`, `Bun.file`, and the full runtime surface.$escape$,
  $escape$// .vscode/launch.json
{
  "version": "0.2.0",
  "configurations": [
    {
      "type": "bun",
      "request": "launch",
      "name": "Debug index.ts",
      "program": "${workspaceFolder}/index.ts",
      "stopOnEntry": false,
      "watchMode": false
    }
  ]
}

// Or from CLI — attach Chrome DevTools
// bun --inspect-brk index.ts$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
