INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '74283bfb-88d9-47c2-bd40-c7e37add1e8d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Bun — When It's the Right Runtime and When It Isn't$escape$,
  $escape$Bun wins when cold-start latency and throughput matter. Its JavaScriptCore engine starts ~4× faster than Node, making it ideal for CLI tools, edge-deployed API servers, and scripts that run constantly in CI. `Bun.serve()` handles HTTP with zero dependencies — no Express, no Fastify — and ships with native `bun:sqlite`, `Bun.file()` streaming, and a built-in test runner. TypeScript runs directly without a `tsc` step, so iteration is instant.

Bun struggles when your stack depends on native `.node` addons (e.g., `bcrypt`, `sharp` in some configs) — these require Node-ABI bindings Bun doesn't fully replicate. If you're on AWS Lambda with a Node 20 runtime, you can't swap Bun in without a custom layer. `reflect-metadata` for NestJS decorators has known edge cases. Bun also lacks Node's LTS guarantee — APIs evolve faster, which matters for regulated or long-lived production systems.

Bottom line: greenfield HTTP services, CLIs, and TypeScript monorepos — pick Bun. Existing Node apps with native bindings or platform-locked runtimes — stay on Node.$escape$,
  $escape$// Bun-native HTTP server with SQLite — no npm installs needed
import { Database } from "bun:sqlite";

const db = new Database("app.db");
db.run("CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS hits (path TEXT, ts INTEGER)");

const insert = db.prepare("INSERT INTO hits VALUES ($path, $ts)");

Bun.serve({
  port: 3000,
  fetch(req) {
    insert.run({ $path: new URL(req.url).pathname, $ts: Date.now() });
    const count = db.query("SELECT COUNT(*) as n FROM hits").get() as { n: number };
    return Response.json({ hits: count.n });
  },
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
